{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513243"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12068"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12068"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.14,0.06,0.12,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4628"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103950"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4628"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12068"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86356"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9091"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44533"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103950"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of colicky, generalised abdominal pain and distension. She feels nauseated but has not vomited. She has a medical history of splenectomy for trauma five years ago and a melanoma excised from her back two years previously. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 94/min, blood pressure 132/86 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended and soft, with numerous high-pitched bowel sounds. A plain abdominal X-ray shows numerous loops of dilated small bowel. Intravenous fluids are commenced and the patient is kept nil by mouth. A non-contrast CT scan is undertaken as part of the assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following CT scan findings would be most suggestive of the need for urgent surgical intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A transition point in the distal ileum","A massively dilated stomach","A non-obstructing lesion in the caecum","Thickening of the wall of the distal ileum","A target sign"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and radiological features of mechanical small bowel obstruction. While adhesive obstruction is the most common cause in patients with previous abdominal surgery, other causes must be considered. CT scan plays a crucial role in determining the underlying cause and assessing the viability of the intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u0027target sign\u0027 has a number of different causes, depending on the type of imaging used and the part of the body being studied. In the present situation of a non-contrast CT imaging study of the abdominal cavity, the \u003Cstrong\u003Etarget sign\u003C/strong\u003E is a radiological term describing the appearance of an intussusception. This is characterised by concentric alternating echogenic and hypoechoic bands. Here is an example (Image). In adults, intussusception is most often caused by a tumour or polyp acting as a lead point. This case has been ongoing for four days and is unlikely to resolve spontaneously. Moreover, there is often an ischaemic component, making urgent surgical intervention necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etransition point\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the site where obstructed, dilated intestine meets normal bowel. This finding alone doesn\u0027t define the underlying cause or indicate the need for surgical intervention. Most cases of adhesive small bowel obstruction resolve with conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emassively dilated stomach\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically a surgical emergency and can often be managed with nasogastric tube decompression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThickening of the wall of the ileum\u003C/strong\u003E could suggest an ischaemic process if accompanied by clinical signs such as fever, tachycardia, hypotension, and abdominal tenderness. However, this patient\u0027s presentation doesn\u0027t strongly support such a diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-obstructing lesion\u003C/strong\u003E in the caecum in an older patient raises concern for a tumour. While most such cases will eventually require surgical intervention, it wouldn\u0027t typically be as urgent as an intussusception unless the mass was causing complete obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the target sign is the most concerning finding in this scenario, as it indicates intussusception which, in adults, usually requires prompt surgical management to prevent complications such as bowel ischaemia and perforation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adult intussusception is most often due to a tumour or polyp and typically requires surgical intervention.","The \u0027target sign\u0027 on CT scan is characteristic of intussusception."],"references":["Hong H, Mike M, Kusanagi H, et al. Adult Intussusception: A Retrospective Review. World J Surg 2015;39:134-38. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25192846/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86356"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12068"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21917"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21917"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fgbPFj5M1Shk288JAPbMSC92ZOY3Yj.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fgbPFj5M1Shk288JAPbMSC92ZOY3Yj.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":527,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86356"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T05:19:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T05:20:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4628"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103950"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel